and c тЙе 0 }` (a convex cone in `тДЭ┬│`).\n   - Set `x i = (i, 0, 0)`.\n   - Set `y s = (-i, 0, 1)` if `i тИИ s`, and `(-i, 0, 0)` otherwise.\n\n   But again, `y s` depends on `i`.\n\n   Maybe if instead `y s = (0, 0, 1)` if `s тЙа тИЕ` and `(0, 0, 0)` otherwise, but:\n   - For `i тИИ s`, `x i + y s = (i, 0, 1)` is not in `C` because `i тЙа 0` (unless `i = 0`, but not for all `i`). \n\n   Not good.\n\n   There seems to be a misunderstanding here: `y s` is a function of `s` only, not of `i`. The condition must hold for all `i` and all `s`.\n\n   So perhaps: for any fixed `s`, `x i + y s тИИ C` must hold exactly when `i тИИ s`. \n\n   So, if `i тИИ s`, `x i + y s тИИ C`, and if `i' тИЙ s`, `x_{i'} + y s тИЙ C`.\n\n   A good way to ensure this is if `x i` are all distinct and `y s` can adjust to map them in or out of `C`. \n\n   But in our case, the condition must hold for all `i`, so if `i тИИ s`, then `x i + y s тИИ C`; but for any other `j тИИ s`, we also have `x j + y s тИИ C`. \n\n   Hmm.\n\n   Let's try to find a way to encode membership in `s` in the sum `x i + y s`.\n\n   Here's another approach:\n\n   - Set `C = { (a, b, c) | a тЙе 0, b тЙе 0, c тЙе 0 }`.\n   - Set `x i = (-i, 0, 0)` (but then `x i` is fixed and `y s` can adjust).\n   - Now, set `y s = (i + 1, 0, 0)` if `i тИИ s`, else `(0, 0, 0)`.\n\n   No, `y s` would have to be `(i + 1, 0, 0)` for all `i тИИ s`, but that doesn't make sense because it must not",
